    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "66969a83_edd3cdab",
        "filename": "sk8s/go/bot_config/adb/adb_test.go",
        "patchSetId": 10
      },
      "lineNbr": 16,
      "author": {
        "id": 5395
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-02-10T14:35:04Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "These tests are hard for me to understand. To make them follow G3 guidelines, I recommend the following:\nRemove the concept of wantErr - if your parameterized test assertions have an if, it\u0027s recommended to split them into two tests http://go/tott/572\n\nWhen doing a parameterized test, follow the example of this Gold web_test [1]. Create a local function that does the interesting bits with the input and output, then create several lines that call that function with the input data. This has the small upside of making it easier to debug, since you can set break points more easily before the failing case, but I also find it easier to read.\n\nFinally, we want to make sure unit tests are easily understandable by people who are not familiar with the code (future maintainers, new people on the team). The recommended naming convention (http://go/unit-test-practices#naming) recommends the test name be quite verbose; it should describe the input and the expected output. If you look at web_test [1], you\u0027ll see that Leandro and I have started to do this for Gold and I think it\u0027s worth it to try to spread this around.\nFor example,\nTestProperties gets split into two tests, like\nTestProperties_ValidResponses_ReturnsExpectedMap\nTestProperties_DisconnectedResponse_ReturnsError\n\nTest_packageVersion also gets split into two tests (even though it\u0027s unexported, we don\u0027t need to encode that in the test name)\nTestPackageVersion_ValidResponses_ReturnsExpectedSlice\nTestPackageVersion_DisconnectedResponse_ReturnsError\n\nand likewise for TestDimensionsFromProperties.\n\nOnce you have the names, it sometimes makes it clear which cases you haven\u0027t tested well (e.g. should there be a TestProperties_InvalidResponses_???? case?)\n\nSeeing all the inputs/outputs lined up on single lines instead of a big list might help you notice other cases (for versions, we only return 0 or 1 versions - should we add a case with 2 or more?)\n\n[1] https://github.com/google/skia-buildbot/blob/b6431980612b5759c745f525993fdeb164e8da09/golden/go/web/web_test.go#L1019",
      "revId": "75592448cffe9b7c2aeabfa47321f00ebc3f1aee",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
